passages.text: ULTAs 2Q25 beat on Sales, GM, OM, and EPS, with robust comp growth of \(+6.7\%\) driven by increased transactions and higher average ticket, while seeing growth across all its categories. FY25 EPS guidance was raised by \(+5\%\) at the midpoint due to the 2Q25 outperformance. We reiterate our OW.

ULTABEAUTY Unleashed Strategy Gaining Traction; Reiterate OW. We recently upgraded shares of ULTABE from EW to OW (Glow- Up; Upgrade to Overweight - 22 Aug 2025) based on: 1) return to sustainable positive comps and margin expansion; 2) improvement in promotional activity; 3) focus on optimizing points of retail distribution by slowing own- brand stores as well as the non- renewal of the ULTAs Target partnership in August 2026; 4) relatively tariff- insulated versus the rest of our coverage, particularly the retailers with exposure to Southeast Asian sourcing; and 5) initially conservative FY25 guidance with opportunity for "beat and raise" quarters for the rest of the year. ULTAs 2Q25 results checked off these boxes as: 1) comps were \(+6.7\%\) with the expectation for comps to be flat to +LSD in 2H25; 2) GM was \(+90\) bps y/y as the company saw higher merch margin as it reduced promotional activity; and 3) beat 2Q25 consensus expectations and raised the full- year with opportunity for upside as the company continues to execute on its ULTABEAUTY Unleashed strategy. The company's strategic initiatives are clearly gaining traction, with successful execution of key promotional events, new product launches, and the secular growth of health and wellness trends, positioning ULTAtore turn to its dominant position as the omichannel leader in the beauty segment. ULTAs one of only two specialty multi- brand beauty retailers in the U.S. market (the other being Sephora in the prestige segment). With ULTAs wide range of price points and category offerings, it is a vital distribution channel for both mass and prestige beauty brands, as such we remain OW rated. In reaction on 8/28/25, in the aftermarket ULTAs shares traded \(+3.7\%\) versus S&P 500 flat.

Tariffs Exposure Update. ULTAManagement did not comment on tariffs as the company has very limited tariff exposure as only \(- 1\%\) of its merchandise was direct imported in FY24, suggesting minimal direct- cost tariff risk.

Quarter in review. EPS of \(\) 5.78\(beat consensus of\) \ \(5.11\) as sales and GM came in better than expected. Sales of \(\) 2.79\(bn was ahead of consensus of\) \ \(2.68bn\) as comp sales of \(+6.7\%\) (vs. cons. of \(+3.0\%\) ) was driven by a \(+3.7\%\) increase in transactions and \(+2.9\%\) average ticket growth. margin of \(39.2\%\) beat (vs. cons. \(38.1\%\) ) due to lower inventory shrink and higher merchandise margin, but was partially offset by deleverage of supply chain costs and other revenue. SG&A rate of \(26.8\%\) matched consensus, though SG&A dollars were slightly ahead due to higher incentive compensation, store payroll and benefits, and corporate overhead. Management raised its FY25 guidance, with revenue guided to \(12.0bn - 12.1bn\) (from prior \(11.5bn - 11.7bn\) and vs. cons. of \(11.7bn\) ), comp growth of \(+2.5\) to \(+3.5\%\) (from prior flat to \(+1.5\%\) and vs. cons. of \(+2.3\%\) ), OM in the range of \(11.9\%\) to \(12.0\%\) (from prior \(11.7\%\) to \(11.8\%\) and vs. cons. of \(12.0\%\) ), and adj. EPS of \(23.85 - 24.30\) (from prior \(22.65 - 23.20\) and vs. cons. of \(23.78\) ).

Inventory. Based on our proprietary inventory analysis, ULTA has posted six consecutive quarters of negative sales- to- inventory growth. In FY2Q25 the Inventory Management Spread ("IM Spread") was (673) basis points and improved from (761) basis points in the prior quarter. ULTA's Gross Margin Return on Inventory ("GMROI") has worsened for six consecutive quarters, and its Operating Margin Return on Inventory ("OMROI") has worsened for six consecutive quarters.

EPS estimates for FY25, FY26, and FY27 are \(24.30, 27.31,\) and \(30.84\) (from \(23.71, 26.79,\) and \(30.20\) ) respectively, as we flow through the 2Q25 beat and raise our sales assumptions. Our PT of \(\) 617\(was\) \ \(589\) ) is based on an NTM P/E multiple of \(20x\) (from \(22x\) ) applied to our CY27 adj. EPS estimate of \(30.84\) (from CY26 adj. EPS estimate of \(26.79\) ). Our multiple is a turn below the current NTM P/E multiple of \(21.0x\) , as we roll forward our PT, which is now based on our CY27 EPS estimate vs. our prior CY26 estimate.

From a fundamental perspective, we use our proprietary PRISM cycle as a leading indicator of potential sales inflection (i.e., either from positive to negative or negative to positive). Our PRISM Curve attempts to look for fundamental changes in the business model of a company, driven by proactive management decisions to stabilize margins (e.g., purge inventory, cut costs, share best practices, invest in product and brand). Figure 2 and Figure 3 below depict our model graphically and identify where we would theoretically expect to see sales and margin changes along the business model curve.

During the HUNT Phase, management's strategy is on the offense. They are in "HUNT" mode and are in control of taking market share. Management is focused on driving company- specific strategies forward, building on their own brand equity and positioning, rather than focusing primarily on competitors or the environment around them. At this point, retailers are usually beating sales and margin expectations and may begin to grow earnings faster than total sales. Investors would want to hold and accumulate shares of a company in Region C in Figure 3, the area of maximum potential stock appreciation. This phase may take place over multiple years as the company enters its sweet spot.

Tariffs Exposure Update. ULTA management did not comment on tariffs as the company has very limited tariff exposure as only \(\sim 1\%\) of its merchandise was direct imported in FY24, suggesting minimal direct- cost tariff risk.

Prior tariff commentary. ULTA has very limited tariff exposure as only \(\sim 1\%\) of its merchandise was direct imported in FY24, suggesting minimal direct- cost tariff risk. The company has previously disclosed that it relies on China imports only for select hair care tools, store fixtures, and store supplies. As such, overall risk remains negligible and well below the rest of our coverage universe as the company's key categories, such as beauty and personal care products have limited China and Southeast Asia exposure (i.e., K- beauty and J- beauty); we do note that some product is imported from Europe.

Barclays Tariff "QuikCalc" Model assumptions. We have updated our Tariff "QuikCalc" model analysis, which now assumes global tariff assumptions effective 8/7/25. Our prior tariff analysis had assumed \(30\%\) China and \(10\%\) Rest of World (excluding Mexico and Canada). Note our estimate of Tariff on Goods Imported to the US is a gross unmitigated amount for a full year, and we calculate the price increase necessary to mitigate full tariff cost (absent other mitigation strategies). Our updated tariff calculator under 8/7/25 effective rates, suggests that for ULTA, total average unit cost will increase by a negligible \(\sim 0.2\%\) with pass- through to the U.S. market only increasing prices by \(\sim 0.1\%\) (see Figure 8).
